  {
    "id": "koc2012-q014",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "dns",
    "stem": "The main function of the DNS server in the Internet Computing is:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "To convert IP addresses to hostnames",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "To convert PC identification",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "To connect your terminal or PC to the Internet world",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "To resolve hostname to IP address",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "DNS's main job is forward resolution: it maps a hostname such as www.example.com to an IP address so packets can actually be routed. Option A is the trap, IP to hostname is reverse DNS (PTR lookup), a secondary capability rather than the main function.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 14
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "eb33ac24e9bc6a2f797d887ebd7f8193a95886bb"
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q015",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "modem",
    "stem": "The main function of a modem from engineering point of view is:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "To connect from one destination to another",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "To convert binary codes to hexadecimal codes",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "To convert analog signals to digital signals and vice versa",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "To convert binary codes to ASCII codes",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "Modem is short for modulator/demodulator: it modulates outgoing digital data onto an analog carrier for transmission over an analog line, and demodulates the incoming analog signal back into digital data. It performs no code conversion (binary to hex or ASCII), which rules out B and D.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 15
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "ab716e74e7d730176497adcd0435f56a7ef4976c"
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q041",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "logic-gates",
    "stem": "In two input OR Gate, if both inputs are 1, what will be the output?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Zero",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "One",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Two",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Unknown",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "OR outputs 1 whenever at least one input is 1, so 1 OR 1 = 1. Do not confuse OR with XOR: XOR would give 0 here because it outputs 1 only when the inputs differ.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 41
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "604ff7dc43a8368b5c9cd0797dcb88e183772d6d"
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q042",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "logic-gates",
    "stem": "If two input NOR Gate, if both inputs are 1, what will be the output?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Zero",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "One",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Two",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Unknown",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "NOR is OR followed by NOT: 1 OR 1 = 1, then inverted gives 0. A NOR gate outputs 1 only when both inputs are 0.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 42
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "27d87d576dc95d041b0b67ede57d199822ceb3d7"
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q043",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "flip-flops",
    "stem": "What do R and S stand for in RS-flip flop?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "R- Reset; S- Set",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "R- Reset; S- Snooze",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "R- Rest; S- Set",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "R- Rest; S- Snooze",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "In an RS (SR) flip-flop, S is Set (drives Q to 1) and R is Reset (drives Q to 0). The other options are nonsense words placed to catch careless reading.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 43
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "d7f52e6a4b195d43e9121f9039a51581ff6b0d7c"
  },
  {
    "id": "koc2012-q044",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "flip-flops",
    "stem": "What will be the output from RS-flip flop under the condition of R=1 and S=0 ?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "The output is reset to zero",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "The output is set to one",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "The output is set to zero",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "The output is reset to one",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "R=1 with S=0 asserts the Reset input, so Q goes to 0. Option C is the trap: 'set to zero' misuses the word set, which in flip-flop terminology specifically means driving the output to 1. Note R=1 and S=1 together is the forbidden/invalid state.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 44
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "cb96bb9295f9aaaf3709ac4b652b2e18b7b1d59f"
  },
